=== Opportunities and Challenges

The long COVID–ME/CFS convergence creates both opportunities and risks:
    - *Opportunity — research acceleration*: Long COVID funding is generating insights directly applicable to ME/CFS. Treatments developed for long COVID PEM will likely benefit ME/CFS patients
    - *Opportunity — diagnostic legitimacy*: The recognition that viral infection can produce chronic multi-system illness validates the ME/CFS disease model and may reduce clinical stigma (see @subsec:psychosocial for full analysis of stigma mechanisms in ME/CFS)
    - *Risk — diagnostic erasure*: Some clinicians may subsume ME/CFS under the “long COVID” label, potentially erasing decades of ME/CFS-specific research and patient identity for non-COVID-triggered cases
    - *Risk — research silos*: Long COVID research conducted without awareness of the existing ME/CFS literature risks repeating solved problems and missing established pathophysiological knowledge
    - *Challenge — heterogeneity*: Combining ME/CFS and long COVID populations in research may increase sample heterogeneity if post-COVID patients include those with organ damage (pulmonary fibrosis, cardiac injury) rather than the functional multi-system dysfunction characteristic of ME/CFS


